[@punkmonk](@EaYYQo5nAQRabB9nxAn5i2uiIZ665b90Qk2U/WHNVE8=.ed25519)

That's super cool, I haven't spent much time thinking about dithering but it would be fun to experiment with.

On a related note, I've recently been annoyed by the state of fonts on the web: most of us are using devices with great fonts, but if you load an site without any `font-family` declarations you get *Times New Roman* or something similar.

There's a new pseudo-font called `system-ui` that uses the [native system font](https://drafts.csswg.org/css-fonts-4/#system-ui-def), but it's [not very well supported yet](https://caniuse.com/#feat=font-family-system-ui). In an effort to get a mostly reasonable default across most operations systems, here's what I've been using lately:

```css
body {
  font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", "Roboto", "Oxygen", "Ubuntu", "Cantarell", "Fira Sans", "Droid Sans", "Helvetica Neue", sans-serif;
}
```

This takes up a small amount of bandwidth, but it's negligible compared to the usual practice where the browser has to download a bunch of custom fonts just to avoid [looking ugly](http://www.motherfuckingwebsite.com/). I'm really looking forward to just declaring `font-family: system-ui` and avoiding the problem entirely!
